Package edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic

Class Unknown

java.lang.Object
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic.Unknown
All Implemented Interfaces:
Expression, Logical, Parameter, Simplifiable, Typed, Value, Serializable, Comparable<Logical>
public class Unknown extends Object implements Value
Unknown is a value that represents a missing or empty value. Fluents of every type can be assigned this value, except fluents of type boolean, which must always be true or false. Unknown always evaluates to itself. Unknown is of every type except boolean.

Unknown should be treated similarly to the concept of null, and does not really enable true reasoning about uncertainty. For example, when we say a character believes a fluent's value to be unknown, this means the character believes the fluent has no value, not that the fluent can have any value. Unknown does not provide a way to circumvent the requirement that effects by deterministic.

Author:
Stephen G. Ware
